rganized by familial and marital connections, women's 'honor' is a form of symbolic capital within a 'political economy' in which marriage organizes intergroup connections. Drawing on statistical analysis of original data contextualized with historical and anthropological readings, Payton explores forms of marriage and their relationship to 'honor', sketching changing norms around the familial control of women from agrarian/pastoral roots to the contemporary era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFamily violencezIraqzKurdistān. 0aFamily violencezIraqzKurdistān. 0aHonor killingszIraqzKurdistān. 0aHonor killingszIraqzKurdistān. 0aKinshipzIraqzKurdistān. 0aKinshipzIraqzKurdistān. 0aMarriagexEconomic aspectszIraqzKurdistān. 0aMarriagexEconomic aspectszIraqzKurdistān. 0aWomen, KurdishxViolence againstzIraqzKurdistān. 0aWomen, KurdishxViolence againstzIraqzKurdistān. 0aWomen, KurdishzIraqzKurdistānxSocial conditions. 0aWomen, KurdishzIraqzKurdistānxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aKhan, Deeyah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, Deeyah1 aBerta, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069033040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978801752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978801752.jpg  a978-3-11-069033-0  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK